 3 Mistakes To Avoid When Setting Up A Living Trust | How To Protect Your Assets            How To Protect Your Assets Menu       3 Mistakes To Avoid When Setting Up A Living Trust What Exactly Is A Living Trust?A living trust is a document that like a will, specifies the desires of the estate owner (known legally as a grantor) except that these desires are specified while the grantor is still living. A grantor may indicate through a living trust that he or she wants heir John Doe to inherit a specific piece of property upon the grantor’s death, for example. While a living trust may not be the best solution in all cases involving estates, there are some benefits to it.   Why Should You Have A Living Trust?A primary reason why many grantors choose to do this is so that their heirs can avoid the probate costs and time associated with traditional wills. Sometimes individuals with involved family or financial decisions can benefit by using a living trust instead of a will. And if a grantor suddenly becomes ill or incapacitated during his or her lifetime, then a living trust allows the grantor’s trustee to make estate decisions on his or her behalf.Living Trusts Can Be Both Convenient And ComplicatedA living trust is designed to be administered by an individual other than the grantor. In this type of trust’s case, the individual is known as a successor trustee. It is the responsibility of this trustee to see that the terms of the living trust are carried out per the grantor’s wishes, upon his or her death. It is possible to disperse an estate while the grantor is still living. This type of living trust is known as an irrevocable living trust, and can reduce estate taxes for heirs. Doing so means that the grantor is permanently giving away property and cannot legally reclaim it. A revocable living trust allows the grantor to retain control of the estate and make changes to the trust right up until the time of his or her death. In this case, estates don’t have to go through probate, but are taxed. Whatever trust type that you’re interested in, be aware that it’s easy to make mistakes that can render the document invalid.Errors To Beware In Preparing A Trust1. You don’t legally establish that you are placing specific property in a living trust.If you don’t do so, then it’s not valid. In other words, it’s not enough to simply tell everyone you’re leaving John Doe your house. This is why it’s an excellent idea to hire an attorney to prepare this trust for you.   2. Your trust doesn’t state specific instructions.Remember, there is a reason why you are placing money or property in a trust. If those reasons aren’t clearly stated (you’re leaving John Doe that house so that he can run it as a cat sanctuary), then the trust isn’t legally binding.3. You don’t keep the trust updated.Finances change and families both grow and shrink, so it’s important to review such trusts annually, preferably with the assistance of an attorney. Other Things To Keep In MindTrusts must also be “funded” (something such as property or money must be officially placed in the trust) before it can be binding. And trusts without specifically named beneficiaries (that’s you, John Doe!) generally aren’t honored by courts. And make sure that you allow yourself plenty of time for the setting up of such trusts, just as you would a will. Remember, in both cases, this may be your last chance to provide for and protect loved ones.          Tweet        Recent Posts 3 Mistakes To Avoid When Setting Up A Living Trust How A DAPT, Domestic Asset Protection Trust, Can Protect Your Assets From Creditors. 3 Things To Know Before Setting Up An Irrevocable Trust Form An LLC And Protect Your Personal Assets Asset Protection Planning: The Basics To Get You Started The Dos And Don’ts Of Setting Up A Trust Fund? Learn About Revocable Living Trusts And Why They Should Matter To YouCategoriesAsset ProtectionEstate PlanningFamily TrustIrrevocable TrustLiving TrustLLCRevocable TrustTrust FundTypes Of Wills      